he Sūrsāgar.This award-winning translation reconstructs the early tradition of Surdas’s verse—the poems that were known to the singers of Surdas’s own time as his. Here Surdas stands out with a clarity never before achieved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aReligious poetry, BrajvTranslations into English. 7aPOETRY / Subjects & Themes / Inspirational & Religious.2bisacsh1 aHawley, John Stratton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074970040uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674293212?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674293212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674293212/original  a978-3-11-074970-0  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK